        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/navid-zamani/{size}/31913_2.png",
        "created_at": "2023-07-16T14:20:00.383Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I‚Äôve now come across the third unsolved bug, that was acknowledged as an actual problem, that was just killed by ‚Äústale bot‚Äù because it was ‚Äútoo old‚Äù.</p>\n<p>So a bug is not a bug anymore, if it is ignored for long enough??</p>\n<p><em>Who</em> in the world though this was a good idea?? ^^</p>\n<p>It doesn‚Äôt even solve the ‚Äúproblem‚Äù of reducing the number of bug reports to manage. Because people are just going to open up new bugs right away. Which, as always, leads to duplicates. So all it does, it create more duplicates. (A kinda Hydra problem.)</p>\n<p>Or is the alternative, of just not using Signal anymore because it is too bug-ridden, a better solution? I don‚Äôt want Signal to become Firefox. (RIP)</p>\n<p><strong>This needs another solution.</strong><br>\nLike, if you guys are just overwhelmed with bugs, there needs to be a priority system (based on your goals, so bugs can be marked as ‚Äúno time‚Äù), and/or a bug bounty system (where people can vote for a bug with their money, and anyone can take it up).<br>\nAnd any but the most pressing bugs can wait until those systems exist, otherwise they never will, as by definition, you‚Äôd still be flooded with bugs until they are.</p>\n<p>(I think bug trackers, in general, need a way to pledge money for bugs. Like Patreon light, but one for each feature, bug, etc. Just an uncomplicated micropayment button next to the bug, and a trustee that sends the money to whoever the money pledges agree has solved the bug. But of course there needs to be a solution for the harmful ‚Äústale bot‚Äù until that happens. [It needs to <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Ofesgkhikg\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">die. With petrel</a>.])</p>",
